      "id": "switch-intro",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 5. The `switch` Statement\n\nWhen you have many specific values to check (not ranges), `switch` can be cleaner than many `if-else-if` statements.\n\n### Syntax:\n```java\nswitch (variable) {\n    case value1:\n        // code for value1\n        break;\n    case value2:\n        // code for value2\n        break;\n    case value3:\n        // code for value3\n        break;\n    default:\n        // code if no case matches\n}\n```\n\n### Important:\n- The `break` statement exits the switch. Without it, execution \"falls through\" to the next case.\n- `default` is like `else` - it runs if no case matches (optional but recommended).\n- Switch works with: `byte`, `short`, `int`, `char`, `String`, and enums.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "switch-intro"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "c7750391-f851-4fd4-8002-873c79d14c48",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Deeper: What is `switch`? (Definition)\n\nA `switch` selects one of many code paths based on the value of a single expression. It's most helpful when you compare the same variable against many specific constant values.\n\n**Real-world applications**:\n\n- Menu-driven programs (ATM, CLI menus) where the user picks a numbered option.\n- Protocol or message handlers where a message type determines the action to take.\n- Mapping codes to labels (HTTP status codes → messages, error codes → handlers, day/month numbers → names).\n- Simple state machines with a small set of discrete states.\n\n**Idea and logic behind using `switch`**:\n\n- Readability: groups all value-based branches together so it's easier to scan than many `else if` statements.\n- Intent: shows clearly that one variable is being matched against constants, which documents your design choice.\n- Maintainability: adding or removing cases is straightforward and localized.\n- Performance: for large numbers of cases the compiler can optimize a `switch` (e.g., jump tables); this is a secondary benefit.\n\n**When to consider `switch` (practical guidance)**:\n\n- Use `switch` when you are comparing the same variable against several discrete constant values (typically 3 or more cases).\n- Prefer `if-else` or range checks when conditions involve ranges or complex boolean expressions (e.g., `x > 10 && y < 5`).\n- Prefer modern switch expressions (arrow `->`) when you need concise, expression-style returns (Java 14+).\n\nQuick rule of thumb: If you're matching one variable to many constants, use `switch`. If you're testing ranges or different variables, use `if`/`else if`.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "c7750391-f851-4fd4-8002-873c79d14c48"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "switch-example",
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "// Day of the week\nint dayNumber = 4; // 1 for Monday, 2 for Tuesday, ..., 7 for Sunday\nString dayName;\n\nswitch (dayNumber) {\n    case 1:\n        dayName = \"Monday\";\n        break;\n    case 2:\n        dayName = \"Tuesday\";\n        break;\n    case 3:\n        dayName = \"Wednesday\";\n        break;\n    case 4:\n        dayName = \"Thursday\";\n        break;\n    case 5:\n        dayName = \"Friday\";\n        break;\n    case 6:\n        dayName = \"Saturday\";\n        break;\n    case 7:\n        dayName = \"Sunday\";\n        break;\n    default:\n        dayName = \"Invalid day\";\n}\n\nSystem.out.println(\"Day \" + dayNumber + \" is \" + dayName);",
