      "id": "1bb9995a-4a3e-4dcd-8304-87de6a106f4d",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Key Takeaways: Preventing Double Debit\n\n| Pattern | Number of Customers | How It Works |\n|---------|-----------|-------------|\n| **Idempotent Transactions** | < 1,000 customers | Check transaction log before processing. Same ID = skip. Simple, single-server friendly. |\n| **Provisional Debit** | 1,000 - 100,000 customers | Deduct tentatively, confirm after API response, rollback on failure. Handles moderate scale. |\n| **Database Constraints** | 100,000 - 1M customers | Use database unique constraint on `(account_id, transaction_id)`. Enterprise-grade reliability. |\n| **Message Queues** | > 1M customers | Queue withdrawal request, retry only if acknowledgment fails. Distributed, highly resilient systems. |\n\n**Best Practice for ATM/Banking:**\n1. Always generate a unique transaction ID on client side.\n2. Check transaction log *before* processing.\n3. Deduct balance.\n4. Log the transaction.\n5. Send confirmation to user.\n6. If network fails, user can safely retry → system detects duplicate and blocks it.\n\nThis is why real ATMs show \"Do not remove card\" during transaction—they're confirming the network handshake before finalizing the debit.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "1bb9995a-4a3e-4dcd-8304-87de6a106f4d"
      }
