    {
      "id": "62a4eef8-27bb-4264-9872-7ebf2e21f5e8",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "### Banking & Microfinance: Which Pattern to Use?\n\n**Microfinance Banks** (10K – 500K customers):\n- **Primary Choice: Database Constraints** (100K – 1M customer range)\n- **Secondary: Provisional Debit** with confirmation for extra safety\n- Key: Use database-level `UNIQUE` constraint on `(account_id, transaction_id)` as the safety net\n\n**Commercial Banks** (1M+ customers):\n- **Combination of ALL four approaches**:\n  1. **Message Queues** – Route all withdrawals through a reliable queue (prevents request loss)\n  2. **Database Constraints** – `UNIQUE(account_id, transaction_id)` as the ultimate safeguard\n  3. **Idempotent Transaction IDs** – Client sends unique ID; server checks before processing\n  4. **Provisional Debit** – Optional extra layer for high-risk transactions\n\n**Why Database Constraints Matter Most:**\n- Enforced at storage layer (cannot be bypassed, even if application code has bugs)\n- Multiple server instances can process requests in parallel without coordinating\n- Prevents double debits even if all other safety checks fail\n\n**Real-world example flow:**\n```\nCustomer at ATM/Mobile App\n    ↓\nGenerate unique TXN-ID (e.g., TXN-20260221-12345)\n    ↓\nSend to API Server\n    ↓\nServer: Check if TXN-ID exists in transaction log\n    ↓\nMessage Queue: Enqueue withdrawal request\n    ↓\nDatabase: Process transaction\n  → Check UNIQUE constraint on (account_id, txn_id)\n  → Deduct balance\n  → Log transaction\n    ↓\nConfirmation: Send back to customer\n    ↓\nIf network fails: Customer retries with same TXN-ID\n  → Database detects duplicate TXN-ID → REJECTS it\n  → Balance protected ✓\n```\n\n**Real-world insight:**\nMajor banks (ICICI, HDFC, State Bank, ICBC, Wells Fargo) use all four patterns combined—but the database unique constraint is the **non-negotiable foundation**. This is why ATMs show **\"Do not remove card during transaction\"**—they're confirming the network handshake before finalizing the debit.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "62a4eef8-27bb-4264-9872-7ebf2e21f5e8"
      }
    },
